Putting together the results of the previous sections we obtain the following classification of $T_n$ in terms
of the CM property:

\begin{teo}\label{main}
For triangular graphs $T_n$, the following holds:
\begin{itemize}
\item[(i)] $T_2$, $T_3$ and $T_5$ are CM graphs. 
\item[(ii)] $T_7$ and $T_9$ are CM graphs over any field of characteristic zero.
\item[(iii)] $T_4$, $T_6$, $T_8$ and $T_n$, for $n\geq 10$, are not CM graphs. 
\end{itemize}
\end{teo}
\begin{proof}
The theorem follows from propositions \ref{3,5 are CM}, \ref{7,9 are CM}, \ref{even not CM}, and \ref{non CM n>11}. 
\end{proof}

\begin{rem}
Using $\mathtt{SINGULAR}$ 
$\mathtt{4}$-$\mathtt{0}$-$\mathtt{2}$, we verified that $T_7$ is CM over some fields of positive characteristic, such as
${\mathbb F}_2$, ${\mathbb F}_3$ and ${\mathbb F}_5$. In every case, we found explicit regular sequences using symmetric polynomials (see appendix). This fact suggests 
that $T_7$ and $T_9$ might be CM over any field, giving a complete classification of $T_n$ in terms of the CM property. 
\end{rem}







